Jenkins Freestyle Job 
Tasks: Pull code from GitHub, run build commands, archive artifacts. 
Outcome: Automated builds 

Aim 
To create and execute a Jenkins Freestyle job by pulling source code from GitHub and running 
build commands in order to understand automated build execution using Jenkins. 

Theory 
Jenkins is an open-source automation server that supports Continuous Integration by 
automatically executing build tasks. 
A Freestyle Job is the simplest Jenkins job type and is configured using a graphical interface. 
It is mainly used for basic automation such as compiling code and viewing build outputs 
through the Jenkins console. 

Procedure / Steps 
Step 1: Create GitHub Repository 
• Create a GitHub repository named Github_Bankservice. 
• This repository stores the source code used by Jenkins. 

Step 2: Add Java Source File 
• Create a file named BankService.java in the repository and add the given Java code. 
• This program demonstrates a simple bank account operation for build execution. 

Step 3: Open Jenkins Dashboard 
• Open Jenkins in the browser and click New Item. 
• This starts the job creation process. 

Step 4: Create Freestyle Job 
• Enter job name: GitHub_BankApplication 
• Select Freestyle Project 
• This creates a basic Jenkins job. 

Step 5: Add Job Description 
• Enter a short description for the job. → Helps in identifying the purpose of the build. 

Step 6: Configure Source Code Management 
• Select Git and enter GitHub repository URL 
https://github.com/username/Github_Bankservice 
• Jenkins pulls source code from GitHub. 

Step 7: Add GitHub Credentials 
• Enter GitHub Username and Password 
• Allows Jenkins to authenticate and access the repository. 

Step 8: Specify Branch to Build 
• */main or */master 
• Defines which branch Jenkins should build. 

Step 9: Add Build Step 
• Select Execute Windows Batch Command 
• Enter: 
o javac BankService.java 
o java BankService 
• Compiles and executes the Java program. 

Step 10: Save and Build 
• Build now → Starts the job execution. 

Step 11: View Console Output 
• Click the build number → Console Output. 
• Displays compilation and execution results.

Step 13: Execute the JAR File 
• cd target 
• java -cp sample-app-1.0-SNAPSHOT.jar com.bnmit.BankService 
• Executes the packaged Maven artifact.

