Jenkins Build Triggers 
Tasks: Configure SCM polling and GitHub webhook. 
Outcome: Automatic build triggering. 

Aim 
To understand and configure Jenkins build automation by enabling SCM polling and GitHub 
trigger options so that builds are automatically triggered when changes occur in the GitHub 
repository. 

Theory  
Jenkins is a Continuous Integration tool that automates building and testing of applications 
whenever source code changes. 
A build trigger defines when a Jenkins job should run automatically. 
• SCM Polling allows Jenkins to periodically check the repository for changes and trigger 
builds if updates are detected. 
• GitHub trigger option enables Jenkins to respond to repository events (used here 
conceptually without actual webhook configuration). 
These triggers eliminate manual build execution and improve automation efficiency. 

Procedure / Steps 
Step 1: Create GitHub Repository 
• Create a new GitHub repository named Github_Bankservice. 
• This repository acts as the SCM source for Jenkins. 

Step 2: Add Java Source File 
• Create a file named BankService.java in the repository and add the given Java code. 
• This program is used to demonstrate build execution and output validation. 

Step 3: Create Jenkins Job 
• Enter item name: GitHub_BankApplication 
• Select Freestyle Projec 
• Freestyle project allows easy trigger and build configuration. 

Step 4: Configure Source Code Management 
• Select Git under Source Code Management 
• Enter Repository URL - https://github.com/username/Github_Bankservice 
• Add GitHub Username and Password in Credentials 
• In Branches to build, specify: */main or */master 
• Jenkins needs repository access and branch details to fetch source code. 

Step 5: Configure Build Triggers 
• Under Build Triggers, select: 
o GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling 
o Poll SCM 
• Enter schedule: * * * * * 
• SCM polling checks for changes every minute and triggers build automatically when 
changes are detected 

Step 6: Configure Build Steps 
• Select Execute Windows Batch Command 
• Enter: 
o javac BankService.java 
o java BankService 
• Compiles and executes the Java program during each build. 

Step 7: Save and Build 
• Build Now → Open Console Output to verify execution 
• Confirms correct job configuration and successful build. 

Step 8: Trigger Automatic Build 
• Modify the Java code in GitHub (e.g., change withdrawal amount from 200 to 100) 
• Commit and push changes 
• Jenkins automatically detects the change through SCM polling and triggers a new build. 

Step 9: Verify Updated Output 
• Check the console output of the latest build 
• Verify output reflects updated code 
• Confirms automatic build triggering is working correctly 
